english:
  title: Record of the Eastern Pavilion at Gongju
  author: Seok Sikyeong-am
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Every great prefecture must have a Pavilion for Welcoming Spring. When winter passes and the ninety-fifth day arrives, the three yings awaken, ten thousand things begin to stir—this is called the Beginning of Spring. Before this time, the prefecture appoints officials to prepare clay oxen, metal and wooden farm implements, vegetables, fruits, wine, and offerings in abundance. The responsible clerks, bearing their records, oversee that nothing is neglected. Then the magistrate and his deputy lead all the senior officials and soldiers east beyond the town walls, each in proper dress to perform the rites. Thus they serve the spirits of land and grain, practice the ways of farming, and later receive taxes and settle accounts, bestow favor and celebrate the joy of the realm—all the year's affairs are laid before them. Surely no place suits this better than such a pavilion.

    Every great prefecture must also have a Pavilion for Receiving Guests. When inspection officials or royal envoys—great or small—pass through, the prefecture commands all soldiers and senior officials to raise their banners, don their regalia, and go forth to meet them at the distant borders. The deputy and magistrate, with their staff, dressed in proper robes, hasten to welcome them respectfully, standing in order at the near fields. They compose themselves, perform the rites with solemnity and reverence, maintain harmony between host and guest, and observe the proper ranks of high and low. Thus they greet and bid farewell—and truly, such a pavilion is indispensable for this.

    Now Gongju was once the seat of a great regional commander. The Dragon Mountain rises to the southeast, the Bear River enfolds it to the southwest. The earth here nurtures spiritual grace and beauty. Through many generations it has grown, and from ancient times to now has become a great prefecture. Two hundred paces east of the town lies waste ground—tradition says it was once the site of the Spring Pavilion. The foundation stones and steps have crumbled, weeds and brush have overgrown it. Through a hundred magistrates it remained unbuilt, abandoned to ruin.

    Then Min Sangbaek of Yeohung came as regional commander. Within less than a year, order was restored and the administration flourished. In his spare moments from general duties, he distributed orders to assemble workers and conscript labor. All the neglected and crumbling halls, storehouses, schools, temples, and pavilions throughout the town were repaired and restored.

    The magistrate declared: "Consider that I, as governor, stand as leader of the people and bear the charge to encourage farming. I cannot neglect to set an example of agricultural virtue for them. Moreover, this prefecture sits at the crossroads of two provinces, and is known as a flourishing center—thus the rites of receiving and sending off guests are of great importance. The Eastern Pavilion enables both these essential functions. Nothing is more urgent. Let construction begin here."

    Thereupon the clerks gave their all, the workers labored with full strength. They gathered without waiting for the summons drum, worked diligently without need of overseers' whips. Timber floated down from the upper reaches, tiles were fired on the eastern slope. The magistrate himself went there dawn and dusk, directing this way and that, adjusting the proportions. Considering the terrain's eastern inclination, he raised the guest pavilion there and turned the main hall southward. East and west galleries, south porches—fourteen rooms in all. Places for changing clothes, places for serving food, heated chambers for winter, cool halls for summer. Then they raised the earthen platform, plastered the walls, and applied red lacquer. The scale was neither too broad nor too narrow; the finish neither plain nor excessive. On the level courtyard with its layered steps and covered walkways, above one could perform the rites, below one could conduct affairs.

    When the pavilion was complete, all who passed by paused to praise it, and many sang this song as they departed:

    "When the magistrate governs Gongju, the prefecture flourishes.
    The people remember his virtue and vie to sing his praise.
    He urges them to farm and secures their livelihood.
    He receives the royal envoy and serves the throne's commands.
    See this pavilion and know the magistrate's governance—
    His rule takes this pavilion as its mirror."
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The Beginning of Spring (立春) occurred on the ninety-fifth day after the winter solstice in the traditional East Asian calendar, marking the start of the agricultural year.
  - key: ''
    value: The clay ox ceremony (土牛) was an important ritual performed by regional authorities to encourage farming and ensure agricultural prosperity.
  - key: ''
    value: Min Sangbaek (閔祥伯) served as a regional commissioner (刺史) in Gongju, which was a significant prefecture with historical importance as a former seat of military authority.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'two provinces' refers to administrative divisions through which Gongju passed as a transportation hub, making it a crucial point for receiving official envoys and conducting regional affairs.
